{"wing":"project","room":"software-engineering","content":"When debugging a rendering flicker (content flashes one style then snaps to another), the root cause is often a markup mismatch between client-side parse and server-side re-parse of the same input. The client renders its version first, then replaces it with the server's version once the round-trip completes — producing a visible flash.

Diagnostic pattern: reproduce in offline mode. If the flicker disappears (the "wrong" style persists indefinitely), it confirms the server returns structurally different markup that the client's renderer processes differently. The fix is to make the client's parser produce markup consistent with the server's output, not to mask the flicker with CSS.

This applies broadly to any rich-text/render system where the same source text is parsed independently on two sides of a network boundary — not just chat markdown.","importance":3,"source":"engineering-decision"}

